\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf2 A 
\f0\b tablespace
\f1\b0  is a directory on the file system that stores data files for database objects like tables and indexes. Using different tablespaces can help with performance by spreading I/O load across multiple storage devices or by placing frequently accessed data on faster disks (e.g., SSDs).\
To create a tablespace, you first need a directory on the file system that the PostgreSQL user has write access to.Then, use the \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 CREATE TABLESPACE\cf2 \cb1 \strokec2  command.
\fs48 \cf5 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf6 \cb7 \strokec6 CREATE\cf3 \strokec3  \cf6 \strokec6 TABLE\cf3 \strokec3 SPACE fastdata LOCATION \cf8 \strokec8 '/mnt/ssd/pg_fastdata'\cf3 \strokec3 ;\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 To use the tablespace, you specify it when creating a database, table, or index.
\fs48 \cf5 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf6 \cb7 \strokec6 CREATE\cf3 \strokec3  DATABASE myapp_db TABLESPACE fastdata;\
\cf6 \strokec6 CREATE\cf3 \strokec3  \cf6 \strokec6 TABLE\cf3 \strokec3  mytable (id \cf6 \strokec6 INT\cf3 \strokec3 ) TABLESPACE fastdata;\
\cf6 \strokec6 CREATE\cf3 \strokec3  INDEX myindex \cf6 \strokec6 ON\cf3 \strokec3  mytable (id) TABLESPACE fastdata;\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 To drop a tablespace, all objects within it must be dropped or moved to another tablespace first.\\
\fs48 \cf5 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf6 \cb7 \strokec6 DROP\cf3 \strokec3  TABLESPACE fastdata;\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

