\f0\b\fs36 \cf2 Patching and Upgrades
\fs28 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 Patching
\f1\b0  typically refers to applying minor version updates (e.g., from 14.1 to 14.2) that fix bugs and security vulnerabilities. 
\f0\b Upgrades
\f1\b0  involve moving to a new major version (e.g., from 13 to 14), which often includes new features and architectural changes.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf2 Patching (Minor Version Updates)
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf2 \
For minor updates, PostgreSQL's binary compatibility often allows for a simple process. First, stop the PostgreSQL service. Then, install the new package from your operating system's package manager (e.g., \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 apt\cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 , \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 yum\cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 ). Finally, restart the service. This usually doesn't require a data dump and restore.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf2 Upgrades (Major Version Upgrades)
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Major version upgrades are more complex and require careful planning. The most common methods are:\
\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 pg_dumpall and Restore
\f1\b0 : This is the safest method. You dump all databases to a SQL file using \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 pg_dumpall\cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 , install the new version of PostgreSQL, initiali\cf9 \outl0\strokewidth0 s\cf2 \outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 e a new data directory, and then restore the data from the dump file. This is reliable but can be slow for large databases.\uc0\u8232 \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 pg_upgrade
\f1\b0 : This tool is designed to make upgrades faster by rewriting the system catalogue but not the actual data files. It's much faster than the dump and restore method. It requires both the old and new PostgreSQL binaries to be present on the system. You run \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 pg_upgrade\cf2 \cb1 \strokec2  with the old and new data directories specified.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Logical Replication
\f1\b0 : For minimal downtime, you can set up a new server with the upgraded version and use logical replication (or a tool like \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 pglogical\cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 ) to replicate data from the old server to the new one. Once the new server is fully synchronized, you can switch your application's connection to it.\uc0\u8232 
